2025 Outlook:
Ohtani has scripted quite the résumé already over his seven MLB seasons: Rookie of the Year (2018), MVP honors (2021), first player in history to hit 30-plus homers while also striking out 200-plus batters (2022), back-to-back MVPs (2023-24) and, most recently, becoming the charter member of baseball's 50/50 club (2024). While further history book rewrites might seem logically unattainable for the now-30-year-old, it's still within the realm of possibility that he'll score a career-high total fantasy points in 2025 and/or set a personal best in Wins Above Replacement. As both a hitter and pitcher from 2021-23 -- his expected role once again in 2025 -- Ohtani <i>averaged</i> 214 fantasy points more than the league's next-best player annually, an advantage that can be readily exploited in ESPN's standard game with its daily transaction format. Ohtani's fantasy utility hinges heavily upon how your league handles him, but a universal, No. 1 overall case is a relatively easy one.

2025 Outlook:
What toe problem? Judge, who missed 42 games after tearing a ligament in his right big toe crashing into an outfield wall in June 2023, entered 2024 facing legitimate questions about future maintenance of the ailment. Instead, he delivered a season for the ages: MLB-leading numbers in home runs, RBIs, walks (133), OBP (.458), slugging (.701), OPS (1.159), OPS-plus (223) and Wins Above Replacement (10.8). Oh, yes, and a career-high 158 games played. Judge's contact-quality metrics are off the charts -- he has paced the majors in expected wOBA, Barrel and hard-hit rates among hitters with at least as many plate appearances as his in each of the past three seasons -- and he's among the game's most selective hitters, even if his game has lots of swing-and-miss. There aren't many more well-rounded players to select with a first-round fantasy draft pick.

2025 Outlook:
Witt followed up his sizzling, 2023 second-half breakthrough with a 2024 that might have garnered him an MVP award (not to mention top placement on our fantasy leaderboards), if not for Shohei Ohtani and Aaron Judge. Witt became the first player to manage multiple 30/30 seasons before his 25th birthday, and the 11th shortstop of any age with a 30/30 campaign. He led the majors in batting average, and was one of only six players with at least 100 runs scored and 100 RBI. Witt is one of the game's few true five-category rotisserie superstars, his combination of solid contact and extra-base ability affording him the chance to challenge for the fantasy points leaderboard. Plus, he's still only 24 years old. If there's a nit to pick, it's that he attempted only 15 steals across his most recent 94 games (playoffs included), which could be as much small sample size noise as it might signal his seeing more red lights on the bases as his bat becomes more critical to the Royals' competitive chances.

2025 Outlook:
Fresh off his unanimous 2023 NL Rookie of the Year campaign -- one that saw him become the first rookie in baseball history with at least 25 home runs and 50 stolen bases -- Carroll spent the first half of 2024 making a compelling case for fantasy bust of the year. Carroll finally got it together during the second half, hitting .259/.351/.568 with 17 homers and 17 steals in 64 games, a welcome sign that the rotisserie superstar of old had returned. One of the game's most fun, dynamic young talents, De La Cruz burst forth with a historic, breakthrough 2024 that probably didn't even garner the level of attention it deserved. Few players hit the baseball with greater authority than Alvarez. Across six MLB seasons, his 53.2% Statcast hard-hit rate is third-best (minimum 1,000 plate appearances), his 93.5 mph average exit velocity is sixth-best and his 17.1% Barrel rate is seventh-best. Alvarez's main differentiators from the game's elite are his injury history -- he has made seven trips to the IL -- and a lack of hardware, statistical records or a big free-agent contract. That might, however, make him a relative discount among players who deserve selection during the first two rounds.

Chourio's rookie season is tough to appreciate until it's put into the proper context. Harris ultimately bookended his campaign with an impressive month of September in which he slashed .316/.344/.579 with eight homers. He was regularly batting leadoff down the stretch and could very well remain there to begin 2025 with Ronald Acuna expected to miss at least the first month while recovering from knee surgery. A low walk rate threatens to relegate Harris back to the lower third eventually, but if he stays on the field he could finally reach 20-20 with Atlanta after falling just short in 2022 and 2023.

2025 Outlook:
After impressing with his glove in 2023, Doyle broke out as a hitter, joining 19 others in the 20/20 club and one of 10 with 20 HR and 30 SB. His breakout was fueled by a 10-point reduction in strikeout rate (down to 25.4%) while increasing his Hard-Hit rate from the 19th to 58th percentile. The power surge wasn't all Coors Field with 11 of his 23 homers coming on the road, though Doyle's .900 home OPS was much better than his .636 road mark. Trusting a one-year breakout is risky, but Doyle is a standout defender with a stolen base floor and Coors Field at his back.

2025 Outlook:
Yelich's troublesome back finally forced him under the knife in August, ending his season. Specifically, the procedure was a microdiscectomy, a spinal surgery to remove part or all of a bulging or herniated disc. While Yelich was still not cleared to swing a bat as of mid-December, the team is expecting him to be ready early on in spring training. The outfielder produced at a high level in between IL stints last season, slashing .315/.406/.504 with 11 homers and 21 steals in just 73 games. The back now being surgically repaired offers hope that Yelich could stay on the field and return to something close to his previous levels of production, though it would be unwise to expect him to return an MVP level for the Brewers at 33 years old.

2025 Outlook:
Smith's wRC+ declined for the fourth straight season, but his 111 mark was still one of the top efforts from a catcher, especially one with the sixth most plate appearances at the position. With Shohei Ohtani joining the Dodgers, Smith only served as the DH three times. However, there is evidence that his drop in production wasn't necessarily due to the extra games behind the plate. April was by far Smith's best month with a .397 wOBA, then the final five months fell between .279 and .332, with September being his second-best month. Since 2021, only Salvador Perez has had more plate appearances as a backstop and just J.T. Realmuto has caught more innings than Smith, so a gentle drop in exit velocity and Hard-Hit rate is understandable. Even so, Smith's quality and quantity of contact remain solid for the position, keeping Smith among the first backstops off the board.
